Cell["\<\
The creation and annihilation operators raise or lower a state with an energy \
increase or decrease of \[HBar]\[Omega]. They are bosonic ladder operators \
that create or annihilate a photon. We shall explore properties of these \
operators in the following section.\
\>", "Text",
 CellID->116539545,ExpressionUUID->"d51704ed-a7d6-424c-bf38-fa42c7b88541"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Basic properties of creation and annihilation operators ", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.927720462383971*^9, 3.927720469388729*^9}, {
  3.9301377473235016`*^9, 3.9301378093564396`*^9}},
 CellID->154343889,ExpressionUUID->"511a3a0b-2961-0542-8ec7-a7e832fb1461"],

Cell["\<\
In numerical work we approximate the infinite-dimensional Fock space with a \
finite photon-number cutoff, so calculations live in a finite-dimensional \
subspace. The cutoff sets the maximum occupation per mode (or globally across \
modes) and trades accuracy for computational cost. With this choice, basis \
states and operators become finite matrices on the truncated tensor-product \
space.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9695599613941813`*^9, 3.969559980377859*^9}},
 CellID->1606079945,ExpressionUUID->"966274aa-63f4-4a50-83ea-61c1b8d8200c"],

Cell["Set the photon-number cutoff to 12:", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.969559984090927*^9, 3.969559991917996*^9}},
 CellID->804187959,ExpressionUUID->"c6d13e63-f9ef-44d6-a0c6-3626cf015e40"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"SetFockSpaceSize", "[", "12", "]"}], ";"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9301483118963165`*^9, 3.930148317689377*^9}, {
  3.933952693925432*^9, 3.9339527124588566`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[4]:=",
 CellID->529095194,ExpressionUUID->"de459380-81c6-8e42-8572-e9f5f65e6147"],

Cell["\<\
This truncation is the main approximation in what follows: we restrict the \
infinite-dimensional Hilbert space to a finite-dimensional subspace by \
limiting the maximum excitation number.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9579603909638147`*^9, 3.957960401523889*^9}, {
  3.957960472092555*^9, 3.957960497274412*^9}, {3.9690338007558403`*^9, 
  3.9690338726037464`*^9}, {3.969560011887467*^9, 3.969560013313178*^9}},
 CellID->55214204,ExpressionUUID->"953d5019-9afe-5c49-a8d8-0fd0de2a92fa"],

Cell["Use $FockSize to see the current cutoff.", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.969560923456499*^9, 3.969560943090435*^9}, 
   3.9714511139954185`*^9},
 CellID->961221579,ExpressionUUID->"df783df1-cfe6-443e-81ad-e26914adb2dc"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[BoxData["$FockSize"], "Input",
 CellLabel->"In[5]:=",
 CellID->931042883,ExpressionUUID->"8edce5c6-5bd9-4660-a785-94f5b5a76f76"],

Cell[BoxData["12"], "Output",
 CellLabel->"Out[5]=",
 CellID->1440876415,ExpressionUUID->"79bd3217-71e2-4244-b730-3b8950e0eac8"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell["\<\
It means that the state vector of quantum states is a vector of 12 elements. \
Or in other words, we restrict our computation into a 12-dimensional Hilbert \
space.\
\>", "Text",
 CellID->1283284540,ExpressionUUID->"08533821-64ae-4ee8-8925-320bc306745d"],

